<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-201-618  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 201 618.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>PC Week  March 5 1990 v7 n9 p34(1)* Full Text COPYRIGHT Ziff-Davis Publishing Co. 1990.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Datability's changing vista. (Datability Software Systems Inc.andO;introduces Vista Communications Platform modules for terminalservers) (product announcement)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Musich, Paula.andM;</AUTHOR><DESCRIPT>Company:   Datability Software Systems Inc. (product introduction).andO;Product:   Datability Vista Communications Platform (Computer communicationsequipment) (product introduction).andO;Topic:     Wide Area NetworksConnectivityCommunications EquipmentProduct IntroductionMultivendor SystemsX.25 ProtocolTransmission Control Protocol-Internet Protocol (Computer NetworkProtocol).andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>By Paula MusichandM;Datability Software Systems Inc. recently armed its Vista terminal serverswith a multiplicity of connectivity options that users say better equip themto mix and match their network systems.andM;The Vista Communications Platform, originally released as a Digital EquipmentCorp.andP;  Local Area Transport (LAT)-compatible terminal server, is nowavailable with a dual-protocol TCP/IP and LAT network-interface card, aprotocol-translation adapter that translates between TCP/IP and LATprotocols, and an X.25 gateway adapter that supports both LAT and TCP/IPtraffic over X.25 wide area networks.andM;The server's modular architecture allows the different adapters to be mixedor changed without affecting the operation of other adapters being used inthe server, according to officials from the New York-based company.andM;Each of the adapters requires a single network connection from a terminal --or a PC emulating a terminal -- to the Vista server for multiprotocol accessto Unix hosts running TCP/IP and VAX/VMS hosts running DECnet protocols.andM;For installations with both VAX/VMS and Unix hosts, the new network-interfaceadapters provide a lot of flexibility, according to Barry Archer, adata-communications specialist at the University of Missouri at Kansas City.andM;&quot;It makes it much more flexible for us to have dual-protocol support,&quot; saidArcher, who beta tested the protocol-translation and dual-protocol adapters.andM;&quot;Users can log into any host on the network, whether it's running Unix orVMS, and they don't know they're using different protocols,&quot; he explained.andM;Datability Software's dual-protocol TCP/IP, LAT Network Interface Card ispriced at $1,600; the Network Protocol Translator Line Card costs $2,399; andthe X.25 Gateway Line Card is priced at $3,199.andM;Datability Software Systems Inc. can be reached at (212) 807-7800.andO;</TEXT></DOC>